{{Infobox sports team | name = AS Pontoise-Cergy TT | color1 = #43C6DB | color2 = black | logo = | logo_size = | alt = | caption = | full_name = Association sportive de Pontoise-Cergy Tennis de table | nicknames = | founded = 1927 | league = [[Pro A (men's table tennis)|Pro A]] | arena = Hall Omnisports Philippe Hémet | city = [[Pontoise]], [[France]] | president = Louise Adam | coach = Peter Franz | members = 250 | website = {{Official website|http://www.aspctt.com/}} }}
'''Association sportive de Pontoise-Cergy Tennis de table''' (commonly abbreviated '''AS Pontoise-Cergy TT''' or simply '''ASPCTT''') is a [[table tennis]] club based in [[Pontoise]], [[France]]. One of the top clubs in the country, it finished runner-up in the French top division [[Pro A (men's table tennis)|Pro A]] three times (2009, 2010, 2013)<ref name=ettuclub>{{cite web|url=http://www.ettu.org/mens-european-champions-league/clubs/as-pontoise-cergy/ |title=AS Pontoise Cergy Team Profile |publisher=European Table Tennis Union |accessdate=22 April 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218093444/http://www.ettu.org/mens-european-champions-league/clubs/as-pontoise-cergy/ |archivedate=18 February 2014 }}</ref> and also reached the final of the [[European Champions League (table tennis)|European Champions League]], the premier continental competition in Europe in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ettu.org/2014/03/pontoise-allez-angers-chapeau/|title=Pontoise, allez! Angers, chapeau!|publisher=European Table Tennis Union|first=Alex|last=Miletic|date=21 March 2014|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref>
