'''Charles Sackville, 2nd Duke of Dorset''' <small>[[Privy Council of Great Britain|PC]]</small> (6 February 1711 &ndash; 5 January 1769), styled as the '''Earl of Middlesex''' from 1720 until 1765, was a British nobleman, politician, opera impresario and [[cricket]]er.  He was styled Lord Buckhurst from 1711 to 1720 and Earl of Middlesex from 1720 to 1765.

==Early life==
Sackville was the eldest son of [[Lionel Sackville, 1st Duke of Dorset|Lionel Sackville, 7th Earl of Dorset]], created [[Duke of Dorset]] in 1720. He was educated at [[Westminster School]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford]], receiving an [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge)|MA]] in 1730. He then embarked on a [[grand tour]] to Italy, which lasted from 1731 to 1733. While in [[Florence]] in 1733, he established the first [[Freemasonic]] lodge in all of Italy.

==Politics==
He was bitterly opposed, politically, to his father, and ventured to oppose his candidates in the boroughs he controlled. He became an ally of [[Frederick, Prince of Wales]]. In the [[British general election, 1734|1734 election]], he was defeated at [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]], but was returned as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[East Grinstead (UK Parliament constituency)|East Grinstead]]. He was appointed Captain of [[Walmer Castle]] in September. He continued to sit for East Grinstead until 26 May 1741, when he accepted the office of High Steward of the Honour of [[Otford]].

He was returned for [[Sussex (UK Parliament constituency)|Sussex]] in a by-election in 1742, and for [[Old Sarum (UK Parliament constituency)|Old Sarum]] at the [[British general election, 1747|1747 election]]. He served as a [[Lord of the Treasury]] from 1743 until 1747, and was appointed a [[deputy lieutenant]] of [[Sussex]] on 20 October 1745. He was appointed [[Master of the Horse]] to the Prince of Wales in 1747, and served until Frederick's death in 1751. Middlesex married [[Grace Sackville, Countess of Middlesex|Hon. Grace Boyle]], daughter and heir of [[Richard Boyle, 2nd Viscount Shannon]], on 30 October 1744, but they had no children.

During the [[British general election, 1754|1754 election]], he unsuccessfully contested [[Westminster (UK Parliament constituency)|Westminster]], and held no seat until the next election. He returned to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] as Member for East Grinstead from 1761 until 1765.

In that year, he succeeded his father as [[Duke of Dorset]], and also as [[Lord Lieutenant of Kent]], and was made a [[Privy Council of Great Britain|Privy Councillor]] in 1766. However, he did not long enjoy the ducal honours. Upon his death in 1769 in London, he was succeeded by his nephew, [[John Sackville, 3rd Duke of Dorset|John Sackville]].

==Opera==

After a second [[grand tour]] to continental Europe in 1737 and 1738, he returned to England in January 1739 and staged an opera, [[Angelico e Medoro]], with music by [[Giovanni Battista Pescetti]] from a libretto by [[Metastasio]] at [[Royal Opera House|Covent Garden]]. This was intended as a showcase for the (apparently limited) talents of the [[soprano]] [[Lucia Panichi]], ''La Muscovita'', who was Middlesex's mistress from about 1739 to about 1742. He also had the ambition to revive full-scale Italian opera in London, which [[John James Heidegger|Johann Jakob Heidegger]] had recently abandoned at the [[Her Majesty's Theatre|King's Theatre, Haymarket]] because of its expense. Middlesex staged a season in 1739–40 at the [[Haymarket Theatre|Little Theatre, Haymarket]], but he was unable to raise enough subscriptions to continue the next year. For the 1741–42 season he entered into partnership with seven other noblemen (the second [[Opera of the Nobility]]) and they were able to continue for three years at the [[Her Majesty's Theatre|King's Theatre, Haymarket.]]

==Cricket==
Like other members of his family, particularly his brother and his nephew, Sackville had an interest in [[cricket]] but did not achieve their level of involvement, probably because of his political activity.  He is known to have played for [[Kent county cricket teams|Kent]] during the [[1734 English cricket season]] in the match against [[Sussex county cricket teams|Sussex]] which is the earliest known game at [[Sevenoaks Vine]].<ref>McCann, p.15.</ref>  His brother [[Lord John Sackville]] played alongside him for Kent, who won the game; and [[Sir William Gage, 7th Baronet|Sir William Gage]] played for Sussex.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jl.sl.btinternet.co.uk/stampsite/cricket/ladstolords/1731.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=17 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629140105/http://www.jl.sl.btinternet.co.uk/stampsite/cricket/ladstolords/1731.html# |archive-date=29 June 2011 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}. Retrieved on 17 July 2009.</ref>

