{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}
{{Use British English|date=March 2016}}
'''William Fennex''' (born c.1763 at [[Gerrards Cross]], Bucks; died 4 March 1838 at [[Stepney]], London) was a famous English [[cricket]]er.  He was a noted all-rounder and right arm fast bowler.  As a batsman, Fennex was reputed to be one of the first to use forward play and was said to be a good driver of the ball.

His playing career began with [[Berkshire county cricket teams|Berkshire]] in 1785 but he was chiefly associated with [[Middlesex county cricket teams|Middlesex]] and was keeper of the ground at [[Uxbridge]].  He made 85 known first-class appearances until 1800 and then played occasionally, making nine more appearances from 1802 to 1816.

He played for the Players in the inaugural [[Gentlemen v Players]] match in 1806.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/0/316.html CricketArchive – scorecard of inaugural Gentlemen v Players match]</ref>

Like [[William Beldham]], he subsequently provided [[James Pycroft]] with his reminiscences.

